div.font: Define infrastructure as code with Terraform. Deploy with GitHub Actions

div.style: font-size: 12px;
font-size: 12px;
div.font: Two AWS accounts needed for prod/non-prod.Â
div.span: Production account should trust the non-prod account and a have a role that (certain) developers can assume after they sign in to the non-prod account.

div.style: font-size: 12px;
font-size: 12px;
font-size: 12px;

li.font: No Apache httpd server. To check: do we need a resource to replace it (e.g. ALB) or can we do everything via route53/cloudfront?
No VNS3 server - use the AWS portal/EC2 Instance Connect (uses AWS IAM) if you need to ssh

li.span: No Jenkins or OpsWorks - deploy changes with GitHub Actions/Terraform/CodeDeploy instead

li.font: Run the CPM on Fargate (managed ECS) instead of EC2
Run the âinternalâ and âfo-to-pdfâ apps on Fargate instead of sharing the Delta EC2 instances
Actually use the autoscaling groups where we can (Digital Space only uses them for auto-heal)
Deploy MarkLogic using their template for a managed cluster: https://docs.marklogic.com/guide/ec2/CloudFormation
Use AWS Directory Service for the AD domain controllers instead of managing the instances directly. Will replicate the current CA setup for LDAPS (single-tier)
Replacing Squid server with AWS Network Firewall
Replacing the FTP server with S3 (data export to DAP)

div.style: font-size: 12px;
font-size: 12px;

ul.li: We will use VPC Endpoints to securely send requests to AWS services from our VPC. Everything that can live in the VPC will.
We can also use Terraform to configure the Keycloak server, not just create it. It is currently manually configured.

Jaspersoft servers will end up similar to the current setup, just managed differently. E.g. using a cloudformation template and suitable AMIs, similar to MarkLogic:Â
https://aws.amazon.com/quickstart/architecture/tibco-jaspersoft/
But note that the servers were currently significantly customised manually, and are using a version of JS that reached end of life in 2021

Potentially all applications will send logs to sentry/logit, the connections just aren't drawn. They either send the logs directly or send logs to CloudWatch and then a Lambda function would send those logs onwards
